  <title>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">CO-Cholera response</narrative>
  </title>
  <description type="1">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Mozambique is endemic to cholera outbreak however for the last two years there has been no cases recorded. In January this year cases of cholera were recorded at health centers in Maputo and Nampula provinces. Since then cases have continued to increase where by 07/03/2017, 698 cases have been received at health centers and 2 deaths have been recorded. The cases have been noted to continue increasing rapidly in Maputo province. This is linked with the scarcity of water due to ration as the source, a dam has water level very low due to last year drought. This is on the side compounded by start of rainy season that is causing flooding is some part of the city of Maputo and Matola where drainage is not good.
Oxfam has not started any activity with the exception of participating the cholera meetings organised by Ministry of Health on weekly basis. This is mainly due to the reason that Oxfam has no funds to undertake this.


Project description / activities (including numbers to be reached):

UNICEF has approached Oxfam to lead in response in Matola city while they lead in Maputo district in collaboration with ministry of health. UNICEF on one side will support with some chlorine provision however not enough to cover the needs.

Project activities planned in this short term:

1. Increase availability of#certeza# at HH level through mass distribution in all the houses in the most affected barrios
2. During mass distribution of certeza, provide keys messages (1) Treat or boil water (2) Wash hands with soap at critical time (3) Any suspected cases should go ASAP to receive free medical care
2. Use mass media to alert families on cholera risks and prevention messages
3. Do shock chlorination ofwater tanks connected to boreholes
4. Advocate for alternative water supply on short-term considering scarcity.</narrative>
  </description>
